description: Your oasis nestled in the city. Bright, modern open-concept living. 3 Bedroom, 2 balcony, 1.5 bath. neighborhood_overview:
If you’re looking to live in the heart of downtown Ottawa, Centretown is the place to be. Centretown is a leafy residential district with a busy commercial core of clothes stores, brunch spots and lively Irish pubs on Elgin and Bank streets. The Rideau Canal is popular for its waterside trail and becomes an ice-skating rink in winter, while Dundonald and Jack Purcell parks are dotted with monuments and public artwork. The Canadian Museum of Nature has exhibits on Arctic fossils and polar bears.

Centretown’s history is naturally intertwined with the history of Ottawa, and you can see that history anywhere you look. Just north of the “official” boundaries of Centretown are the Parliament Buildings of Canada, the famous Chateau Laurier, the former Ottawa central train station, and historic Sparks St. West of Elgin, you’ll find many of the bank and financial towers that keep the city’s economy moving forward.

As you head further south, the character gradually changes

name: Elcho's Explore Ottawa Luxury for 6 - Parking
description:
Close to Ottawa downtown. The unit is fully equipped, quiet on the 2nd floor duplex of our home.
Kitchen with choice of Bodem Press or Krueger coffee maker, pots, pans, fridge, stove and microwave. Sleeps 6. Parking, "Embassy row", view of Ottawa river, Strathcona Park, 15 mins. walk/1 bus: Byward Mkt, Rideau & Sparks St, Parliament, Hill, Canal, City Hall, Sites.
Parking: One parking spot in driveway at $10/night, $50 flat fee for 5-day+ stay.

*We are Travel Proud hosts.
neighborhood_overview:
Look for the identifying plaques on the heritage buildings throughout Sandy Hill. Range Rd., (Embassy Row) is lined with embassies two of which are our neighbors in the back. Pack a picnic and walk 4 minutes to Strathcona Park where children can be seen playing in its sand castle and swings. In the winter you might catch a glimpse of a cross country skier or two. While at the park, stroll along the Ottawa River, home of ducks and two swans, or walk to the park's entrance on Laurier Avenue and make a wish at the fountain. There are more embassies on Laurier but almost directly across the street is the famous Cordon Bleu Culinary Institute. You will need to make advance reservations for lunch or dinner there. BTW: The stop light that is around the corner from the Russian Embassy is Rideau St. which becomes Wellington St. (Direction West...i.e. left turn), address of the Senate & Parliament, Library & Archives and the Bank of Canada.
At the far end of the park you can cross Ottaw
host_about:
My Mom was the quintessential home maker and host. I learned hosting at her feet in Canada, in the Bahamas, and in Jamaica. I have been hosting friends and family from as far back as high school and college. Yes. Mine was the apartment where friends timed "just dropping in" knowing full well that food, a warm bed, or a respite was always there.  
I'm also a connector/networker and a go-to person who loves people,  travelling, cooking, gardening, interior decorating as well as domestic science. Along with my business degree and over 30 years runnung a Canada-wide financial services brokerage, I've found a perfect fit in accommodations both in Canada and in Jamaica.
I'm also a mom and step-mom of a total of  of 5 Gen-X & Gen-Y, and a grandmother of 6, Daniel's wife, a former financial advisor and financial columnist, a gardening blogger, a socialite, a fashion stylist, a Mistress of Ceremony and a writer. I can manage in French and can count in Spanish...high school Spanish.
Please join me in explOring my little slice of heaven. See you soon.
Cheers!

There are 3 restaurants that do amazing pizza, chinese/thai, and/or breakfast and a general store, LCBO/beer store, pharmacy, and ice cream place. Some guests have seemed shocked that the cottage isn’t right downtown Ottawa with every city amenity imaginable, so I like to forewarn people in case you aren't familiar with the beauty that is Constance Bay.

There is a community centre with a children's and toddler's park a 5 minute drive away. There you will also find a skateboarding park, soccer fields, baseball diamonds, and outdoor rink in the winter.

name: Downtown Canal 2 BDR w/ Parking. Walk Everywhere!
description: Cute, Clean and Cozy two bedroom downtown Ottawa, minutes walk from the Canal, Elgin street, Museum of Nature, Parliament, Grocery stores, banks, pharmacy, liquor, beer store, shopping, bars, restaurants, bike paths and more! Convenient bike rental down the street. On site free parking and unit door codes for seamless 24 hour check in. Fantastic space and location! neighborhood_overview:
You are located seconds away from the canal where you can hop on a bike or walking path for a scenic route to Museums, Lansdowne, The Byward Market, The Glebe, Preston street, Tulip festival, Winterlude and much more.

Parliament Hill and the Byward Market is about a 25 minute walk/5 min drive or ten min bike ride away.

Join some friends for brunch, lunch or dinner, and then hit the shops for the highest quality food products, fashions and cutting edge trends. See and be seen until the wee hours at one of our hip nightspots.
Morning, noon and night the ByWard Market has something just for you.

Established by Lt-Col. John By in 1826, the ByWard Market is one of Canada's oldest and largest public markets. The legendary builder of the Rideau Canal, Colonel By himself laid out the street plan of the Market, designating George Street and York Street to be extra wide to accommodate the creation of a public market and gathering place.

Beaverbrook is bounded by March Road to the north and east, Campeau Drive to the south, and just to the west of Carr, Pentland, Tiffany and Reaney Crescents. Beaverbrook is one of the original neighbourhoods of the former city of Kanata.

The area remained mainly agricultural until the 1960s, when it was developed from rural land that was acquired by Bill Teron. The neighbourhood was built using a model community approach, which made Beaverbrook into an independent neighbourhood that has its own unique character and commercial services.

description:
One of the very few century homes to undergo a complete renovation. There is 2800 sq ft of living area and an attached garage. Guests will find a well stocked kitchen and ample space for relaxing and entertaining. We have removed our personal possessions to allow guests to enjoy the space as their own.

Sep 23 review..”Wow… just … wow…. Your house is spectacular…. Every time I turn a corner I’m shocked…. It’s even more beautiful than the pictures”
neighborhood_overview:
You are in the heart of an established centuries old area called the Glebe, a very hip and urban suburb that really has all you need for entertainment & shopping. Lined by beautiful Victorian style homes with “Ma and Pa” shops from boutiques, bakeries, grocers, banks, pharmacies, specialty cafés, fine dining, casual dining, and pubs.
You are a five minute walk to the scenic Rideau canal, a UNESCO World Heritage Site, where you can bike/walk/run along tree-lined paths or ice-skate in the winter along the longest skating canal in the world.
Parliament Hill is close enough to walk but easy public transit on OC-Transpo (a two-minute walk) will have you there in ten minutes.
The Lansdowne development has brought a new vibe with trendy nightclubs and restaurants, green space with skatepark and play structures, a Whole Foods grocery store and a modern theatre build around the Lansdowne stadium which is home to the Ottawa Red Blacks (CFL), the Ottawa Fury (ASL) and the Ott
host_about: My wife and I have settled back in Canada after eight years of living overseas in India, Dubai and Hong Kong.  We loved our travels but also love Ottawa, our beautiful Canadian capital.  There is so much to do and see here and we live right in the heart of this amazing city!  We look forward to hosting you for your Ottawa visit.  Thankyou, Bart and Ariane

My home is well situated for the adventure crowd or the home body wanting to bring family and friends together around the fire — or the dining table. 

I love my home and I know others love it too!  Please read my reviews. Guests rave about the location, the cleanliness, the amazing host (that’s me!), and the comfort and quality of the beds and furnishings.

I look forward to your stay. 

Bienvenue, Donna Wishart

description:
Discover this bright, modern semi-detached home on Ottawa’s Embassy Row. Located across from Strathcona Park along the Ottawa River, it offers abundant natural light and access to picturesque nature trails for walking/biking. Within walking distance to Byward Market, Parliament Hill, and Ottawa U. It's close to amenities like a grocery store and sports club. (STR 843-269)
neighborhood_overview:
Sandy hill is situated within walking distance of the ByWard Market, so shares many services and shops of the market, including grocery stores and the transitway. Located close to downtown, Sandy Hill has excellent public transportation, a large shopping complex, and many schools to serve its families. Sandy Hill is bounded by Rideau-Besserer-Daly Avenue on the north, both Highway 417 and Nicholas Street to the south, the Rideau River to the east, and the Rideau Canal to the west. This neighbourhood includes the community of Strathcona Heights and the University of Ottawa.
As a residential community, Sandy Hill dates back to the 1870s and was the wealthiest and most prestigious neighbourhood in the Ottawa area up until the early 20th century. Some of the neighbourhood’s notable locations include Laurier House, the residence of Prime Ministers Sir Wilfred Laurier and William Lyon Mackenzie-King, and the house of WWI ace Billy Bishop, which was later inhabited by another Prime Mini

My life’s motto is to be present and live in the moment.  As an artist, I love to create and discover new things and as your host, I have tried to create a modern, minimalist, boutique hotel style experience for you.  I welcome you to my home and I hope you enjoy it as much as I have.

description:
Bright, modern two-bedroom loft. King, Double and sofa bed. Vaulted ceilings. Separate entrance.
Quiet residential street in the heritage neighbourhood of New Edinburgh. Walk to embassies, Global Affairs Canada, restaurants, shops, and parks. Steps to Governor General's official residence. Blocks from the Prime Minister's residence. Short ride to Byward Market, National Gallery, National Arts Centre, downtown - or a pleasant walk along Sussex Drive.
neighborhood_overview: After years of living in different areas of Ottawa, we have fond memories of New Edinburgh.  Our children attended a nearby school and spent innumerable hours after-school at the local ballet academy.  We divided our time between the beautiful running paths alongside the river and the welcoming local pubs.  Our favourite local bakery, The Scone Witch, began in the corner of a nearby house, which now houses the Union Street Kitchen and Yoga Studio.  Although work has taken us away, we maintain our home for our own return visits and we are very happy to make it available to visitors, because we want to share the feeling of living in a warm, familiar setting that we are certain others will appreciate.
host_about:
Professional working couple with four teenage daughters.
Best family vacations have been those that were three weeks or longer.
Last minute planners.  Favourite travel destinations include Paris, Tuscan countryside, cities in Europe and beaches in France, Greece, North Carolina, Cuba and Florida. 
Life motto:  "Whatsoever thy hand findeth to do, do it with thy might..." Eccl. 9:10

name: 5* Apartment, mins from Airport, EY Centre, Casino
description: A unique loft in a rural setting, right in the city of Ottawa. Surrounded by farmers' fields, yet only 7 minutes to the airport & EY Centre, 20 minutes to downtown, 4 mins to the casino, golf, hiking & biking trails. A rustically appointed repurposed airport hangar with rounded ceilings. View brilliant sunsets from the balcony & exercise your pet on the expansive property. Find every amenity such as a workspace, HS internet, AC, & pantry essentials. Retreat to an experience in the country.
neighborhood_overview:
This private apartment is located in a relaxed, country setting, just outside the city of Ottawa. The two acre, property is surrounded by farmland where dogs can run free. There is hiking nearby, in addition to the Osgoode-Leitrim Pathway which can be used for biking, strolling or cross-country skiing. Falcon Ridge Golf Course is a two minute drive down the road. Continue a minute further and you will arrive at the Hardrock Casino and Racetrack. Two local communities, Riverside South and Findlay Creek are both a five minute drive. Both have grocery stores, a variety of shops, restaurants, and park land.
Winterlude is around the corner. From February 2 to 19, Ottawa and Gatineau will be bustling with a host of indoor and outdoor activities that showcase Indigenous culture, Canadian diversity and significant anniversaries. You won't want to miss it!
Coming this Spring...Ottawa Light Rail Transit station, less than 1 km away. Take the train right downtown to the Byward Market.
host_about: Mother to Katie, 21 and Nathan, 19, wife of 24 years to Dan, Vice Principal, teacher...almost retiree. Lived in Australia twice, for a year at a time, on teacher exchanges. Love to travel, decorate, scuba dive, garden and cottage. Building a rental cottage in Quebec. Just joined a home exchange website. Looking forward to meeting our guests from all over the globe and hearing their stories!

name: 103 Acre Woods Marlborough Forest The Cedars
description: Get away from it all when you stay under the stars. Camping at the 103 Acre woods is part of the Marlborough Forest. It has groomed pathways in the meadow and rustic pathways through the woods for your hiking pleasure. Stunning night sky as there is very little light polution. Plenty of birds and nature here. Simply Paradise!
neighborhood_overview:
Camping at the 103 Acre woods is part of the Marlborough Forest. It has groomed pathways in the meadow and rustic pathways through the woods for your hiking pleasure. If you are interested in backwoods camping, it's easy to do here, park your car in the driveway, grab your gear, and head to the back forty!

I only list 2 sites for camping so you will have plenty of space and privacy from any other campers. Lots of space to spread out and have your privacy. If you want complete privacy, reserve both sites! (The Cedars & 103 Paces)

If you are staying in an RV, you can park in the driveway and still access all the other parts of the property. Tent campers can select anywhere they want to pitch a tent and enjoy the beauty of the 103 Acre woods. Depending on where you choose to camp, you might be able to drive right up to your site.

Firepit and wood available for use providing there is no burn ban. Water from the hose attached to the house is available for

name: Great Location in the Glebe - 3 Bed Apt w/ Parking
description:
Large Victorian property (3 bedroom) that has the convenience of downtown. Apartment is located on the 2nd and 3rd floor of the home.

Restored charm with spacious rooms / full kitchen / laundry. Parliament, restaurants, coffee shops, Byward Market, Landsdowne, & the Canal are only a short walk away.

No smoking, no drugs, absolutely NO PARTIES, and a reasonable noise level please.

There is 1 parking spot available on the driveway of the home. EV Charger available (CCS / non Tesla)
neighborhood_overview:
The Glebe has a strong community association which, in addition to running a large community centre, lobbies the local government on issues such as traffic calming and neighbourhood development. The Glebe has a community newspaper, Glebe Report, that has been published independently since 1973.

The Glebe is mostly populated by families; the area has many children, and consequently its social services are oriented towards youth. The Glebe lies in the federal riding of Ottawa Centre, and the same provincial electoral district.

The stretch of Bank Street that runs through the Glebe is one of Ottawa's premier shopping areas, with many small stores and restaurants offering a wide variety of services. Much of the rest of the Glebe consists of detached homes, many of them constructed in the early decades of the 20th century. Some of these homes are owner-occupied family residences, while others have been subdivided into multiple rental apartments.

The Glebe is
host_about:

name: COZY WESTBORO COTTAGE   : UPGRADED 3 BED W/ PRKING
description:
Live in the Heart of Westboro, in this Cozy, charming and FULLY RENOVATED home rooted in history.

You will find yourself on the best part of the Richmond Strip, with only a few steps to some of the city's best restaurants and shopping.

Westboro BEACH is less than 1 km away!
Enjoy biking along the parkway or a short drive to the ski slopes of the Gatineau hills.

Public transit is a stones throwaway with a short Bus / train ride into the Downtown core.

Ample driveway Parking to fit 3 cars.
neighborhood_overview:
Westboro is a hub of activity all year-long, but particularly during the warm weather months.

Enjoy the soft sand, water activities and spectacular sunsets at Westboro Beach on the Ottawa River.

In spring, Westboro Village welcomes all to join in a celebration of retailers during Shop the Village. All summer long, people fill the patios along the main street and shop at the Ottawa Farmers Market on Saturdays at Byron Linear Park. As the leaves change colour in the fall, look out for ghosts, spiders, skulls and more during the annual Wickedly Westboro Scavenger Hunt.

During mild weather, the recreational pathways along the Ottawa River are filled with cyclists, pole-walkers, roller-bladers and runners. In the winter, the section between Westboro and the Canadian War Museum near downtown Ottawa becomes the Kichi Sibi Winter Trail. Cross-country skiers, snowshoers, fat-bikers and walkers all use this groomed snow route. Urban nature at its best!
host_about:
I am experienced Super Host on Air Bnb.

An Interior Designer by profession.
I have a passion for the arts, music , fashion and food.

The spaces My wife ( Julianne) and I create, have a long history to them.
And as such, we take immense pride in their story.

We both love travelling and try to do so when we can get a few moments to breathe between our busy work schedules. That being said, we love to entertain, dine out and experience new things. 

We look forward to Hosting you!

name: Charming Glebe Home with backyard
description:
Permit # STR 827-478

Welcome to our home in the heart of the trendy Glebe! The Glebe is Ottawa's finest downtown neighbourhood. You will be close to everything when you stay including shops, restaurants, the Rideau Canal and Lansdowne Park. Visit Ottawa and stay in this 3 bedrooms, 1.5 bathrooms home away from home.
neighborhood_overview:
You are in the heart of the Glebe, an established centuries-old area of Ottawa. A very hip neighbourhood lined by beautiful Victorian-style homes with diverse amenities including boutiques, bakeries, grocers, banks, pharmacies, specialty cafés, cinemas, fine dining, casual dining, and pubs. You are a five-minute walk to the scenic Rideau Canal, a UNESCO World Heritage Site, where you can bike/walk/run along tree-lined paths or ice-skate in the winter along the longest skating canal in the world.

We have easy access to public transit on OC-Transpo (a two-minute walk) that will take you to Parliament Hill in ten minutes. The Lansdowne development (a two-minute walk) has brought a new vibe to our neighbourhood with trendy restaurants, green space with a skatepark, play structures, a WholeFoods grocery store and a modern theatre built around the Lansdowne stadium which is home to the Ottawa Red Blacks (CFL), Atlético Ottawa (CPL) and the Ottawa Sixty Sevens (AHL). Our location
host_about: Originally from France, I moved to Canada few years ago for work and stay for love. I lived in many countries: Sweden, India, China, Thailand, and the UK. I enjoy meeting new people from all over the world. I hope I will meet you soon!

description: Leaning against the bay window, you can admire the beauty of Ottawa's changing seasons. In addition, you can carry out your work in the coffee bar, and chat with relatives or friends in the sunroom or patio.
neighborhood_overview:
Our house is in the Forbes neighborhood, which is a safe, friendly, and quiet community. There is a well-known private school St-Laurent Academy on the corner of the street, and a kid street playground next to it, which is very friendly to children. A five-minute walk from the neighborhood will take you to the Aviation pathway, it is a Scenic trail and get close to nature in the heart of the city!

Also, living here is very convenient for you. It is close to a shopping plaza, just 5 minutes’ walk. You could find restaurants and shops, e.g., 24 hours MacDonald’s, Tim Horton’s, Swiss Chalet, Pizza Hut, Independent, Farm Boy, Shoppers Drug mart, Dollarama, Beer Store, Shawarma, Vietnamese restaurant, TD Canada Trust, RBC, Desjardins, etc.
host_about:
My name is Kailin, I grew up in China. I used to be the CEO of a media start up company in China, and tired of the hustle and bustle of big city life. I followed my husband Qingwei to Ottawa, Canada and fell in love with the slow living lifestyle here.

Currently, Qingwei is a software engineer, and I am a stay-at-home mom and housing manager, and welcome you from all over the world is my most important job at the moment.


I am sharing with you a set of residences that I like very much. When I saw it at first glance, I couldn't help but want to own it. It is a house built in the 1950s. After several renovations, it became a place with exquisite and casual style. It has its own style and soul.

Here, you not only enjoy the convenience of the urban life circle, but also be completely close to nature! Sitting under the shade of the trees in the sun room reading a book and drinking coffee is my favorite thing to do every day. Whether you're on a business trip, busy with work, or someone who enjoys traveling, you'll love the relaxation here! This home will blow your tiredness away!

Everyone who has lived in the house will say it's great! Hope you all love it as much as I do!

neighborhood_overview:
Great family neighborhood, close to schools and amenities. The atmosphere there is very welcoming, and people of all ages and lifestyles can feel at home there. Orleans is a new part of the city, in that it only became part of Ottawa in 2001. It's located just off of the Ottawa River, just a few miles east of the downtown core.

There are a number of schools there, and the population continues to rise. The shopping center just off the Queensway is one of the most central and significant landmarks in the Orleans area, and part of what make it such a good place for singles, families, and retirees. Lots of restaurants and shopping in the area.

neighborhood_overview:
Arty Hintonburg's shopping and dining scene is centered on the cool boutiques, bistros, vegan cafes and coffee shops of Wellington Street West. At night, locals head to trendy supper clubs and brewpubs. The Great Canadian Theatre Company stages edgy work by local playwrights, while small galleries, studios and street murals reflect the creative atmosphere. Laroche Park hosts fairs and art events.

In its April 2007 issue, enRoute magazine named Hintonburg one of the top ten emerging neighbourhoods in Canada

Westboro's commercial hub, Richmond Road, is a shopping haven, featuring an array of stylish boutiques, eclectic stores, and cozy cafes. It's a place where residents can explore unique finds and savor artisanal delights.

The neighborhood's proximity to outdoor spaces, including Westboro Beach and the scenic Riverwalk, invites residents to enjoy nature within an urban setting. Parks like Laroche Park provide green spaces for relaxation and recreation.

Located on the border between the LeBreton Flats neighbourhood and Centertown West (which encompasses Chinatown and Little Italy).

Le Breton Flats:
Le Breton Flats is an area beside the Ottawa River, known for its sprawling green spaces and for being home to the glass-roofed Canadian War Museum. The annual BluesFest in July, and other music and food festivals, are held in LeBreton Flats Park close by. As well, LeBreton is also connected to the main system of bike pathways which run through the city-- with the Ottawa River as its northern border, you can enjoy biking, walking and skating along the waterfront. With its emphasis on “green living”, LeBreton Flats is pedestrian and bicycle-friendly; 40% of the community is set aside for parks, courtyards, walkways and open space. Welcome to the charming neighborhood of Castle Heights in Ottawa, Ontario, Canada – a hidden gem that offers the perfect blend of urban convenience and serene surroundings. Nestled just east of the downtown core, Castle Heights provides a unique experience for visitors seeking a tranquil retreat within reach of all the city's attractions.

About the Neighbourhood:

Castle Heights is known for its tree-lined streets, well-maintained parks, and a friendly community atmosphere. This residential area boasts a mix of architectural styles, including classic brick homes, cozy cottages, and modern townhouses, creating a diverse streetscape that's a joy to explore. Its peaceful ambiance makes it a favourite among families, couples, and solo travellers looking to experience Ottawa like a local.

neighborhood_overview:
You’ll find plenty of things to do in Bayshore-Belltown. At the eastern border of Belltown is Britannia Park. This Ottawa River recreation area filled with beaches and boating dates back to 1900. It was such a popular summer destination that it sparked the building of Belltown’s cottages in the 1920s.

PARKS AND SHOPPING

Outdoor enthusiasts can visit Andrew Hayden Park along the western edge of Belltown. You’ll find picnickers, a bandshell, and plenty of walking trails for birdwatching. Check for events at the community centre or play some tennis while you’re there.

Do you need to do some shopping? Stop by the busy Bayshore Shopping Centre. Constructed in 1973 with two floors and 123,000 square feet, the mall has since grown to three floors with 883,250 square feet of retail stores.

This wonderfully diverse neighborhood also offers a nice selection of specialty grocery stores in the very walkable Carling Avenue area.

neighborhood_overview:
Located on the border between the LeBreton Flats neighbourhood and CentreTown West (which encompasses Chinatown and Little Italy).

Le Breton Flats:
Le Breton Flats is an area beside the Ottawa River, known for its sprawling green spaces and for being home to the glass-roofed Canadian War Museum. The annual BluesFest in July, and other music and food festivals, are held in LeBreton Flats Park close by. As well, LeBreton is also connected to the main system of bike pathways which run through the city-- with the Ottawa River as its northern border, you can enjoy biking, walking and skating along the waterfront. With its emphasis on “green living”, LeBreton Flats is pedestrian and bicycle-friendly; 40% of the community is set aside for parks, courtyards, walkways and open space. neighborhood_overview: Nepean, a former independent city, is now part of Ottawa in Ontario. It was first established as a township in 1792, which included the central region of Ottawa. However, in 1978, Nepean Township was recognised as a city. Nepean is geographically bordered by the Ottawa River in the north, Robertson Road to the south, the Rideau River in the east, and Herzberg to the north. Nepean had its own library organisation, police department, and fire service until its amalgamation in 2001. Before its inclusion in Ottawa, education here was governed by the Carleton Board of Education. Still, since its amalgamation, it has joined hands with the Ottawa Board of Education and become the Ottawa-Carleton District School Board. The neighbourhood has a diversified community with couples, children, singles, and older people and comprises over 180,000 residents. Nepean has been home to big-ticket industries like Nortel Networks and JDS Uniphase.
